    "narrative": "The LawDog starting lineup for April 29th is anchored by the dual-threat upside of **Lawrence Butler** (73.43) and **Daulton Varsho** (70.72). **Lawrence Butler** projects as our premier play, benefiting from a soft matchup against Wacha and a favorable park factor (+10%) that offsets his low-order placement. Similarly, **Daulton Varsho** earns his high efficiency score by exploiting a prime platoon advantage against Bello, providing necessary pop that elevates him above our baseline starts. While **Cal Raleigh** (67.47) and **Jonathan Aranda** (67.67) face mid-tier arms in Bradley and Williams, both maintain strong ratings thanks to high-leverage lineup positions\u2014notably **Cal Raleigh** leading the charge out of the two-hole. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (65.79) remains a locked-in core play; while his raw score is slightly tempered by the matchup against Rasmussen, the projection models account for his elite SB potential, specifically noting the pitcher\u2019s delivery cadence which creates a green light for aggressive base-running.\n\nThe bench decision-making process today was dictated by a strict adherence to our efficiency floor, resulting in the exclusion of **Masyn Winn** (39.21). Despite his utility, **Masyn Winn** narrowly missed the cut because the matchup against Chandler proved too volatile, triggering a significant penalty to his SP skill coefficient that pulled him below our required 40.0 threshold. We opted to prioritize the high-efficiency platoon edges of **Jonathan Aranda** and **Daulton Varsho** over the raw counting stats of **Gleyber Torres** and **Wenceel Perez**, both of whom were effectively neutralized by the elite xERA of Ritchie (2.08). The primary risk to monitor remains **Geraldo Perdomo** (58.54); while he retains his leadoff spot, his score is the most precarious in the lineup, as any deviation in the game script against Sproat could render his production marginal. We remain thin on bench depth with **Tyler Freeman** confirmed out of the lineup, but our current rotation is optimized to maximize run production and stolen bases against this slate of right-handed starters.",
